In anticipation of next week&rsquo;s Reproducible Science Hackathon at NESCent, I was thinking about Christie Bahlai&rsquo;s post on &ldquo;Baby steps for the open-curious.&rdquo;
Moving from Ye Olde Standard Computational Science Practice to a fully reproducible workflow seems a monumental task, but partially reproducible is better than not-at-all reproducible, and it&rsquo;d be good to give people some advice on how to get started - to encourage them to get started.
So, I spent some time today writing another of my minimal tutorials, on initial steps towards reproducible research.

Yesterday, I saw this tweet by @Ananyo
 Time that biologists stopped telling the public oversimplistic fairy tales on Darwinian evolution, says P Ball (\$) nature.com/nature/journal...  So I clicked the link to the Nature paper and realized, &ldquo;Oh, yeah. I&rsquo;ve got to enter through the UW library website.&rdquo;
But then I thought, &ldquo;Wait&hellip;\$18 for a two-page Nature comment? WTF?&rdquo;
So I tweeted:
 DNA: Celebrate the unknowns, like this Nature comment, which costs \$18.

A university press asked me to review a book manuscript, and the author &ldquo;has asked that we not use electronic copies.&rdquo; So they&rsquo;re going to send me a hard copy.
My response: &ldquo;If you only give me a paper copy, I&rsquo;m going to just scan it and toss the paper. That seems like a waste of time (and paper and postage).&rdquo;
I should probably have said, &ldquo;Then forget it.&rdquo;
Their response included, &ldquo;What you do with it when it arrives I am just going to take a hear-no-evil approach to.
